initial_story:
The Eurovision Song Contest is just around the corner and this year, it's taking place in Malmo, Sweden.

You can find out all about the event right here.

The UK's entry for 2024 is Olly Alexander who'll be performing his song, Dizzy.

But how's he feeling ahead of the big night, where he'll perform in front of 200 million people!

De-Graft sat down with him to find out all about his preparation for the competition.

The Eurovision Song contest Grand Final will be shown on BBC One and iPlayer on Saturday 11 May.
stories:
Olly took a deep breath as he sat down with De-Graft, a small smile playing on his lips. "I'm feeling a mix of excitement and nerves, of course," he admitted. "But I've been working really hard on perfecting my performance of 'Dizzy'. I want to do my best and make my country proud."

He paused for a moment, looking thoughtful. "I've been practicing every day, focusing on my vocals and choreography. I've also been studying past performances to see what works and what doesn't. I know it's a big stage and a huge audience, but I'm ready for the challenge."

As the interview came to a close, Olly's expression turned determined. "I'm going to give it my all on the night. Eurovision is such a unique and special event, and I'm just grateful for the opportunity to be a part of it."

The Grand Final of the Eurovision Song Contest is just a few days away, and fans from around the world are eagerly anticipating Olly Alexander's performance. Will he bring home the win for the UK? Tune in to BBC One and iPlayer on Saturday 11 May to find out!

Olly's voice filled the interview room with confidence as he spoke. "I've been visualizing my performance every day, imagining the energy of the crowd and the excitement of the moment. I've worked with an amazing team to bring my vision to life, and I truly believe we've created something special."

He took another deep breath, his eyes shining with determination. "Of course, there's always the possibility of nerves on the night, but I've learned to channel that energy into my performance. I want to give the best show I possibly can, for my fans and for myself."

Olly paused, a small smile playing on his lips once more. "I know there's a lot of pressure, but I'm ready for it. I believe in my music, in my team, and in myself. And at the end of the day, no matter the outcome, I'll be proud of the hard work and dedication that's gone into this journey."

The clock was ticking down to the Grand Final of the Eurovision Song Contest, and Olly's heart was pounding with anticipation. But no matter what happened on Saturday 11 May, he knew he was ready for the challenge ahead. Tune in to BBC One and iPlayer to witness his incredible performance and cheer him on!

The interviewer, intrigued by Olly's passion and determination, asked, "What message would you like to share with your fans who will be cheering you on from home?"

Olly's face lit up with a warm smile, "I'd like to thank them for their unwavering support. I couldn't have made it this far without them. I encourage them to believe in themselves and their dreams, no matter how big they may seem. With hard work and dedication, anything is possible. Let's make this a night to remember!"

The countdown to the Eurovision Song Contest had begun, and Olly was more ready than ever to take the stage and give the performance of a lifetime.
